{{nihongo|'''Ryōichi Kuroda'''|黒田了一|Kuroda Ryōichi|16 March 1911 – 24 July 2003}} was a [[Japanese people|Japanese]] [[jurist]] and [[politician]] from [[Suita, Osaka]].

==Early life and academic career==
After graduating from [[Tohoku Imperial University]] in 1933, Kuroda was sent to [[Manchukuo]] to be an instructor at a [[service academy]]. He spent five years in a [[Japanese prisoners of war in the Soviet Union|Siberian labor camp]] before he returned to Japan in 1950, and became a professor of law at [[Osaka City University]] in 1956.

==Political career==
Kuroda was elected as [[governor]] of [[Osaka Prefecture]] in 1971, supported by the [[Japan Socialist Party]] and the [[Japanese Communist Party]]. In 1975, he became the first Japanese governor who won reelection with backing only from the Japanese Communist Party. He unsuccessfully ran for a third term in 1979.

While he was in office, Kuroda took positive [[pollution control|antipollution measures]] and introduced free [[medical care]] for the elderly.<ref name="jl">{{cite journal|url=http://www.jlaf.jp/tsushin/2003/1109.html#1109-04|title=黒田了一さんを悼む|publisher=Japan Lawyers Association for Freedom|language=Japanese|last=Ishikawa|first=Motoya|journal={{lang|ja|自由法曹団通信}}|volume=1109|accessdate=28 April 2009|date=1 November 2003|location=Tokyo}}</ref> He rejected a plan to build a missile base in Osaka, for he held a view that the [[Japan Self-Defense Forces|Self-Defense Forces]] were [[Article 9 of the Japanese Constitution|unconstitutional]].

==Later life==
After he left from politics, Kuroda practiced at the bar. He became a member of [[Japan Lawyers Association for Freedom]] in 1981.<ref name="jl"/>

He died of [[pneumonia]] at age 92.

